##Unfortunately, the new pneumonia vaccine you're looking for may not be as fast

Weixin Guokr233

Function introduction, new media of Science and technology industry under the fruit shell. We focus on technology, companies, industries, and people related to new technologies, as reporters, observers, and learners "from the lab to the industrial market. ".

Magnifier team | mastermind
By Zhang Jingyong
Li Tuo | editor
CDC ON UNSPLASH | problem map

As of February 14,2020, the total number of confirmed COVID-19 cases has reached 63,490, with 10,109 suspected cases.

How to quickly eliminate new coronary pneumonia (COVID-19) , let life return to normal? For thousands of years, three lessons have been drawn from the FIGHT AGAINST INFECTIOUS DISEASES:

Through disinfection, isolation and protection, to ensure that no new infections, and then let the epidemic itself disappear;
Even if the infection disease, also can take out the specific effect medicine;
If there are healthy people are not infected, can be injected vaccine, to achieve prevention purposes.

China is working on a three-pronged effort to eliminate the virus's negative effects as quickly as possible. From an economic point of view, the use of vaccines is undoubtedly efficient, low-cost, and does not affect the normal functioning of social life of the optimal solution. There is historical evidence that Enterovirus C polio lacks a specific drug, but is almost eradicated with a sugar pill (a vaccine) .

In fact, more than 20 research teams around the world claim to be working on a new pneumoconiosis vaccine. The faster group is expected to enter clinical trials in April -- as if, of the three artifacts, a vaccine is on its way?

Let's not get ahead of ourselves. It's important to recognize that it's not as fast as you might think, and it takes at least 8 or 20 years for a vaccine to reach the market.

The birth of a vaccine | Blowup Lamp Illustration 2

If new pneumonia was a callous examiner, and humans were test takers, the first question might be: Foshan

What is the time frame for this paper?

In short, vaccine developers hope to beat the virus, but the rapid end of the epidemic could also disrupt development efforts

If the epidemic is over before the vaccine is developed, the vaccine will be useless, and even if the epidemic is not over, the progress of the epidemic control is much faster than when the vaccine is developed, the lack of clinical trials can also make it difficult to continue vaccine development, potentially costing research and drug companies huge sums of money.

Even if a vaccine does come in handy, it can easily be a pyrrhic victory.

Before we get to the new coronavirus vaccine, let's take a look at what happened to H1N1 vaccine company Sinovac.

The H1N1 influenza virus broke out in early 2009, killing nearly 300,000 people. The company's Panflu. 1 Vaccine, the world's first approved H1N1 vaccine, generated $29.7 million in sales in the fourth quarter of 2009.

But the good times didn't last long, and the next year the epidemic was under control, with annual H1N1 vaccine sales falling to $7.2 million, about a quarter of the previous year's level. Gross profits from the vaccine's surge also hit rock bottom, again only about a quarter of the previous year's level.

2010 total profits, chart | 2010 financial report 3

The experience of the SARS vaccine, also a coronavirus, may be a stronger circumstantial case.

Only three SARS vaccine trials have been recorded, according to the National Institutes of Health. Two of them were withdrawn from the trial, and one was only completed in 2007 as a phase I clinical trial, but then came to a screeching halt, both because of the difficulty of recruiting clinical patients and because the market for the vaccine ceased to exist as the SARS virus suddenly disappeared, business and research incentives disappear.

Clinical trials of the SARS vaccine

According to a report by the Ministry of Science and Technology of the People's Republic of China on December 6,2004, the first SARS vaccine in the world was in phase 1 clinical trials at that time, and all of the vaccinated subjects produced antibodies 4. But as you can see from the earnings report of Beijing Kexing bio-products Co. , also a participant in the vaccine development, the SARS vaccine remains in phase 2 clinical phase 3(and, interestingly, kexing biology is once again working on a new coronavirus vaccine) .

Therefore, the time window for developing a new coronavirus vaccine depends on how long the new pneumonia itself can last.

After the emergence of new crown pneumonia, scientific research and medical workers also found the pathogen with the fastest speed in history, and sequenced its gene, but to confirm the gold standard, transmission routes, specific drugs and vaccines, and other follow-up key issues, the origin of the virus and its intermediate host remain a mystery.

Recent papers on new coronaviruses provide a variety of data and model predictions 57. However, the current epidemic is still developing and changing, many potential variables are difficult to consider, so the forecast data is uneven and can not be unified.

Prediction of the impact of transmission interruption and traffic control on the development of the epidemic | Lancet

If history is any guide, a review of the coronavirus epidemic might shed some light.

Since 2000, there have been two large outbreaks of the virus that can infect people: one known as Atypical pneumonia, and another, still sporadically known as Mers.

Many people should still be on the 2003 SARS. In the battle of SARS, from the outbreak officially announced to the crisis relief lasted more than five months, by means of isolation and other means to cut off the spread of the virus ended 8. The MERS outbreak in 2013 showed another trend, with two major outbreaks in the Middle East and South Korea that infected 2,506 people and killed 862, with a death rate of 34.4 percent. 9. Until now, there have been no specific drugs or vaccines approved to treat Mers, and isolation and symptomatic treatment are the only means of controlling the virus.

Consider the SARS epidemic of 17 years ago, five months ago -- if people could successfully develop a new pneumonia vaccine in such a short time, it would be a myth in the history of technology.

WHO's watching?

By contrast, today's multinational pharmaceutical companies are relatively restrained.

Together, GSK, Merck & Co. , Sanofi and Pfizer, the big four multinational pharmaceutical companies produce vaccines that account for more than 90 per cent of the global market.

But after the new coronavirus outbreak, Merck & Co. , Sanofi and Pfizer of the big four chose not to get involved, and GlaxoSmithKline was the only one to announce a new coronavirus vaccine development program, but only very lightly: with the help of CEPI, it has teamed up with University of Queensland to provide adjuvants for its "molecular tweezers" . One notable story: glaxosmithkline was also one of the first companies to market a vaccine for the H1N1 flu virus, but it wasn't really involved in research and development, just selling the vaccine produced by the IDB.

Each of the big minds behind the balance of profits and expenditures, there are also the allocation of resources to ponder.

The latest figures from the big four show that the main focus of each business is still new drug research and development, with the vaccine business accounting for less than a quarter of revenue, the highest GlaxoSmithKline only more than 20% ; In the first three quarters of 2019, Merck & Co.'s only cancer drug, Florida pd-1 inhibitor, Keytruda, had sales of $7.937 billion, more than all of its vaccine businesses combined ($6.161 billion) .

(Note: Merck & Co.'s figures are for the first nine months of 2019 and the rest for the full year of 2019) 
The big companies'respective vaccine businesses | BLOWUP MAPPING 10,11,12,13

Not surprisingly, vaccines against "rapidly circulating and rapidly disappearing" viruses are often thankless, with little long-tail benefit, so multinational pharmaceutical giants are often inactive or even absent altogether.

Historical experience shows that we may not have a lot of time to answer the questions given by NCP, and in the past, the speed of the development of pandemic vaccines was not satisfactory, and even they often failed. However, after this outbreak, a number of companies and institutions have announced plans to develop vaccines.

Where there's gold, there's gold

The big four vaccine companies have handed in almost no papers, but that does not mean there is no chance of success. According to the magnifier team (ID: Guokr233) , the main team, technology and funding sources are as follows:

Put out the table with the magnifier

How confident are these institutions and companies?

The new technology, especially the MRNA vaccine, is a booster for this round of vaccine development. CUREVAC, Moderna, and domestic microbes, all use MRNA technology to develop vaccines, which are faster to develop and produce than traditional vaccines, allowing the synthesis of Multiple Mrna with different antigenic sequences in a short period of time, targeting key viral targets, combined with the new drug-loading technology, the vaccine 14 ~ 15 was prepared.

Vaccine tip:

Conventional vaccines are generally based on whole strains of the virus (including the virus's genes and coat proteins) , such as attenuated vaccines, killed vaccines, and recombinant protein vaccines that target viral protein components. After the traditional vaccine enters the human body, the immune system will take the vaccine as the Antigen to produce the antibody, thus achieves the defense virus infection function 16.

Mrna vaccine refers to the encoding of Antigen Protein Mrna directly as a vaccine, MRNA in human cells encoding antigen protein, which stimulates the immune system to produce corresponding antibodies, to help the body against the virus 17.

Mrna bridging DNA and protein | MODERNA

The COVID-19 vaccine is expected to be ready in 18 months, WHO Director General Covid-19 told a news conference in Geneva on February 11, the Guardian reported. MODERNA, the Jenner Institute at the University of Oxford, as well as the SPM team, said clinical trials would begin in a few months.

Laws and regulations also lower the bar for entry. Article 20 of the latest Vaccine Administration Law of the People's Republic of China stipulates:

"In the event of a particularly major public health emergency or any other emergency that seriously threatens public health, the competent health department under the State Council shall, in the light of the need for the prevention and control of infectious diseases, make recommendations for the emergency use of vaccines, and May, after the organization, demonstration and approval of the pharmaceutical supervisory and Administrative Department under the State Council, urgently use vaccines within a certain range and time limit. "

Of course, even if the temporary lowering of the threshold, it will not fail. The second half of Article fifty-seven of the Act also states:

"For vaccines requiring further research upon approval of an application for vaccine registration, the holder of the license for vaccine listing shall complete the research within the prescribed time limit; if the research is not completed within the prescribed time limit or if it can not be proved that the benefits outweigh the risks, the pharmaceutical supervisory and Administrative Department under the State Council shall handle the matter in accordance with the law until the pharmaceutical registration certificate of the vaccine is cancelled. "

Adequate research funding is also a requirement. Governments are also investing heavily in the development of a new coronavirus vaccine to address the global emergency as soon as possible. National Natural Science Foundation of China Emergency COVID-1919; UK government donation # 20m 20 to CEPI. National Organizations such as the Jack Ma Foundation and the Tencent Holdings are also funding some research teams.

In addition, the nonprofit organization, set up in Davos, Switzerland, in 2017, responded by announcing an expansion of its previous collaboration with Moderna, University of Queensland, Inovio Pharmaceuticals and CUREVAC, new Coronavirus 1421 was overcome with the help of its vaccine development platform technology, followed by glaxosmithkline adjuvant technology, which partnered with the University of Queensland's Molecular Tweezers Technology Platform to develop the vaccine 22. In addition, the CEPI from February 3 to 14, also open a fund for rapid development of a new coronavirus vaccine team 23.

The underlying motivation may be business. In addition to a sense of responsibility for the public health situation, the potential benefits of the vaccine are also the motivations of the The Battle of Shaker Heights. If we can get the lucky goddess's favor and develop the vaccine in time, the strong purchasing power of the Chinese market will bring inestimable economic benefits to the winning enterprises, and it will be an opportunity for foreign enterprises to open the Chinese vaccine market.

Although vaccine development and production is still a long way off, and success is uncertain, the companies that have just started to develop the vaccine have had their first taste: their brand exposure has soared, and their share prices have soared.

Such as Hong kong-listed company Konsino biological shares continued to rise to record highs, before also submitted a share prospectus, to take advantage of the impact of science and Technology and Innovation Board; After the National Institutes of Health announced on February 7th that progress had been made on Moderna's vaccine, its share price soared by more than 10% .

The bystanders continue to stay out of the way, and the players try to turn things around, but the positive effects of such measures as isolation are becoming apparent, and the outcome is likely to be rewritten before they have a chance to make a move. But despite time, there are still many challenges to it —— Harvard

On the one hand, the expected Mrna vaccine is not perfect, so far no Mrna vaccine has been approved on the market. After entering the clinical trial stage, the MRNA vaccine still faces the challenges of poor agreement between animal experiments and clinical results, and the vaccine failure caused by the mutation of RNA virus.

On the other hand, the fact that HPV and influenza vaccines are hard to find suggests that even if a new cap vaccine is developed, it is unclear whether production capacity will meet the huge market demand.

Smallpox has been eradicated through vaccines, but history tells us not to expect too much from vaccines, and to wear masks, wash hands and protect yourself may be a more pragmatic option.

To paraphrase a passage from the game pestilence corporation, where the pathogen has been completely eliminated:

"The world is about to be wiped out of COVID-19 after a terrible plague. Those who have died will not be forgotten. "

Will the choices and efforts of these enterprises be forgotten?

Conventional vaccines are generally based on whole strains of the virus (including the virus's genes and coat proteins) , such as attenuated vaccines, killed vaccines, and recombinant protein vaccines that target viral protein components. After the traditional vaccine enters the human body, the immune system will take the vaccine as the Antigen to produce the antibody, thus achieves the defense virus infection function 16.

Mrna vaccine refers to the encoding of Antigen Protein Mrna directly as a vaccine, MRNA in human cells encoding antigen protein, which stimulates the immune system to produce corresponding antibodies, to help the body against the virus 17.

Mrna bridging DNA and protein | MODERNA

The COVID-19 vaccine is expected to be ready in 18 months, WHO Director General Covid-19 told a news conference in Geneva on February 11, the Guardian reported. MODERNA, the Jenner Institute at the University of Oxford, as well as the SPM team, said clinical trials would begin in a few months.

Laws and regulations also lower the bar for entry. Article 20 of the latest Vaccine Administration Law of the People's Republic of China stipulates:

"In the event of a particularly major public health emergency or any other emergency that seriously threatens public health, the competent health department under the State Council shall, in the light of the need for the prevention and control of infectious diseases, make recommendations for the emergency use of vaccines, and May, after the organization, demonstration and approval of the pharmaceutical supervisory and Administrative Department under the State Council, urgently use vaccines within a certain range and time limit. "

Of course, even if the temporary lowering of the threshold, it will not fail. The second half of Article fifty-seven of the Act also states:

"For vaccines requiring further research upon approval of an application for vaccine registration, the holder of the license for vaccine listing shall complete the research within the prescribed time limit; if the research is not completed within the prescribed time limit or if it can not be proved that the benefits outweigh the risks, the pharmaceutical supervisory and Administrative Department under the State Council shall handle the matter in accordance with the law until the pharmaceutical registration certificate of the vaccine is cancelled. "

Adequate research funding is also a requirement. Governments are also investing heavily in the development of a new coronavirus vaccine to address the global emergency as soon as possible. National Natural Science Foundation of China Emergency COVID-1919; UK government donation # 20m 20 to CEPI. National Organizations such as the Jack Ma Foundation and the Tencent Holdings are also funding some research teams.

In addition, the nonprofit organization, set up in Davos, Switzerland, in 2017, responded by announcing an expansion of its previous collaboration with Moderna, University of Queensland, Inovio Pharmaceuticals and CUREVAC, new Coronavirus 1421 was overcome with the help of its vaccine development platform technology, followed by glaxosmithkline adjuvant technology, which partnered with the University of Queensland's Molecular Tweezers Technology Platform to develop the vaccine 22. In addition, the CEPI from February 3 to 14, also open a fund for rapid development of a new coronavirus vaccine team 23.

The underlying motivation may be business. In addition to a sense of responsibility for the public health situation, the potential benefits of the vaccine are also the motivations of the The Battle of Shaker Heights. If we can get the lucky goddess's favor and develop the vaccine in time, the strong purchasing power of the Chinese market will bring inestimable economic benefits to the winning enterprises, and it will be an opportunity for foreign enterprises to open the Chinese vaccine market.

Although vaccine development and production is still a long way off, and success is uncertain, the companies that have just started to develop the vaccine have had their first taste: their brand exposure has soared, and their share prices have soared.

Such as Hong kong-listed company Konsino biological shares continued to rise to record highs, before also submitted a share prospectus, to take advantage of the impact of science and Technology and Innovation Board; After the National Institutes of Health announced on February 7th that progress had been made on Moderna's vaccine, its share price soared by more than 10% .

The bystanders continue to stay out of the way, and the players try to turn things around, but the positive effects of such measures as isolation are becoming apparent, and the outcome is likely to be rewritten before they have a chance to make a move. But despite time, there are still many challenges to it —— Harvard

On the one hand, the expected Mrna vaccine is not perfect, so far no Mrna vaccine has been approved on the market. After entering the clinical trial stage, the MRNA vaccine still faces the challenges of poor agreement between animal experiments and clinical results, and the vaccine failure caused by the mutation of RNA virus.

On the other hand, the fact that HPV and influenza vaccines are hard to find suggests that even if a new cap vaccine is developed, it is unclear whether production capacity will meet the huge market demand.

Smallpox has been eradicated through vaccines, but history tells us not to expect too much from vaccines, and to wear masks, wash hands and protect yourself may be a more pragmatic option.
